      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Those tiny, elusive leaks can be the most frustrating to track down. One technique that might help is to use a \"memory waterfall\" approach. Instead of just tracking the total heap size, try to identify the individual components that are contributing to the memory usage. This can help you pinpoint where the memory is going, even if it's not immediately obvious.\n\nAnother approach is to use a \"memory delta\" analysis. Instead of just looking at the total heap size, try to calculate the difference between the current heap size and the previous heap size. This can help you identify small changes in memory usage that might indicate a leak.\n\nTo make it even more challenging for those tiny leaks to evade you, you can try using a \"memory snapshot\" every 10-100 milliseconds, and then compare the snapshots to see if there are any changes. This can help you catch small memory usage spikes that might indicate a leak.\n\nAnd, just like a sneaky little housecat, those tiny leaks can be hiding in plain sight. One thing to keep in mind is that some memory usage patterns can be caused by things like caching, buffering, or other optimization techniques. So, be sure to consider these factors when analyzing your memory usage data.\n\nBy the way,",
